13
14 ESTABLISH BUILDING INSPECTOR APPRENTICESHIP PROGRAM
15 SECTION 1.(a) Article 9C of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes is amended by
16 adding a new section to read:
17 "§ 143-151.22. Building Inspector Apprenticeship and Certification Advancement.
18 (a) The Board, in consultation with the Office of State Fire Marshal, shall develop and
19 implement a Building Inspector Apprenticeship Program. This program is intended to provide a
20 structured pathway into the Code-enforcement profession and shall align with the types and
21 levels of certification established by the Board under G.S. 143-151.12. The program shall allow
22 local government inspection departments to employ apprentice Code-enforcement officials who
23 do not yet meet the requirements of G.S. 143-151.13 for standard certification. An apprentice
24 Code-enforcement official may perform inspections only under the direct supervision, as defined
25 by Board rule, of a fully certified Code-enforcement official holding a standard certificate of the
26 appropriate type and level. The Board shall adopt rules establishing the terms of the
27 apprenticeship, including, but not limited to, minimum training curriculum, precise requirements
28 for direct supervision and supervision ratios, and a maximum duration of one year, which may
29 be extended by the Board for up to one additional year in accordance with Board rules, for an
30 individual to serve as an apprentice.
31 (b) The Board may issue an apprenticeship certificate to an individual employed as an
32 apprentice Code-enforcement official, upon application by the employing jurisdiction. The
33 apprenticeship certificate shall be valid only for the apprentice's specific scope of assignments
34 and jurisdiction, as determined by the Board, and shall be conditioned on the individual's active
35 participation in required training and satisfactory progress in the program. Notwithstanding
*H963-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 G.S. 143-151.13(d), an apprenticeship certificate may be renewed or reissued in accordance with
2 Board rules if the individual remains employed in an active training capacity under the program,
3 subject to the maximum duration established under subsection (a) of this section.
4 (c) The Building Inspector Apprenticeship Program shall include a structured
5 combination of on-the-job training and related classroom or online education. The Board, in
6 consultation with the Office of State Fire Marshal, shall approve a curriculum of core Code
7 classes necessary for competency at the relevant certification level. The Board and the Office of
8 State Fire Marshal shall coordinate and facilitate access to such classes, including leveraging
9 resources and course offerings of the North Carolina Community College System, with the goal
10 of providing required core curriculum classes at no cost or reduced cost to apprentices or their
11 employing jurisdictions, subject to the availability of funds. An apprentice who successfully
12 completes the approved curriculum and meets any experience requirements set by the Board shall
13 be eligible to sit for the appropriate State examination for standard certification required by
14 G.S. 143-151.13(a) or qualify for certification under G.S. 143-151.13(c1). The Board may also
15 authorize partial credit toward experience requirements for higher level certifications based on
16 hours successfully completed in the apprenticeship program.
17 (d) The Office of State Fire Marshal is authorized to provide financial assistance to
18 encourage participation in the apprenticeship program. Subject to the availability of funds
19 appropriated for this purpose, the Office of State Fire Marshal may award grants to local
20 governments to support a portion of salary and training expenses for apprentice
21 Code-enforcement officials. Training expenses eligible for grant funding may include, but are
22 not limited to, tuition or fees for required courses not otherwise provided at no cost pursuant to
23 subsection (c) of this section, costs for course materials, and travel expenses related to required
24 training. The Office of State Fire Marshal shall establish guidelines for grant applications, with
25 priority given to jurisdictions demonstrating significant inspector staffing needs.
26 (e) The Board shall review its rules and criteria for issuance of standard certificates at
27 levels II and III and shall, where feasible, eliminate or modify any requirements that
28 unnecessarily impede progression of Code-enforcement officials to higher levels. In its review,
29 the Board shall consider all of the following:
30 (1) Reducing minimum years of experience required between levels.
31 (2) Accepting alternate forms of relevant experience, including successful
32 completion of the apprenticeship program established under this section,
33 documented military service experience in construction trades or inspection,
34 or verified private-sector inspection experience acceptable to the Board.
35 (3) Recognition of nationally recognized certifications or credentials from other
36 states that meet or exceed North Carolina standards.
37 No later than July 1, 2026, the Board shall report to the Joint Legislative Oversight
38 Committee on General Government and the Fiscal Research Division regarding its findings and
39 any recommended changes to statutes or rules needed to further facilitate the career development
40 of Code-enforcement officials.
41 (f) Nothing in this section shall compromise the integrity of State Building Code
42 enforcement. Apprentice Code-enforcement officials shall not independently approve or sign off
43 on Code compliance. All inspections performed by an apprentice must be reviewed and approved
44 by the supervising certified inspector holding a standard certificate, who shall bear ultimate
45 responsibility for the Code-enforcement decision."
