42 PROVIDE FINALITY TO BUILDING INSPECTIONS
43 SECTION 4.(a) G.S. 160D-1113 reads as rewritten:
44 "§ 160D-1113. Inspections of work in progress.
45 (a) Inspection Authority and Access. – Subject to the limitation imposed by
46 G.S. 160D-1104(d), as the work pursuant to a building permit progresses, local inspectors shall
47 make as many inspections thereof as may be necessary to satisfy them that the work is being
48 done according to the provisions of any applicable State and local laws and of the terms of the
49 permit. In exercising this power, members of the inspection department have a right to enter on
50 any premises within the jurisdiction of the department at all reasonable hours for the purposes of
51 inspection or other enforcement action, upon presentation of proper credentials. If a building
House Bill 963-First Edition Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 permit has been obtained by an owner exempt from licensure under G.S. 87-1(b)(2), no
2 inspection shall be conducted without the owner being present, unless the plans for the building
3 were drawn and sealed by an architect licensed pursuant to Chapter 83A of the General Statutes.
4 (b) Finality of Approved Inspections. – If any component or element of construction has
5 passed a required inspection and been approved by a local inspector (or by the inspection
6 department) as compliant with the State Building Code and applicable law, that approval shall
7 be binding and final as to the Code requirements for that stage of construction. No subsequent
8 inspection shall require the uncovered re-inspection, alteration, dismantling, or removal of the
9 approved component or element, nor shall any inspector or inspection department rescind or
10 withhold approval for such component or element, except upon the occurrence of one of the
11 following conditions:
12 (1) Change in Code Requirements – A material change in the applicable State
13 Building Code or other governing law takes effect after the date of the
14 inspection approval, and retroactive compliance with the new provision is
15 expressly required or is necessary for life-safety reasons.
16 (2) Fraud or Misrepresentation – The inspection approval was issued on the basis
17 of false or misleading information, misrepresentation, or fraud which, if
18 known at the time, would have caused the inspector to withhold approval. This
19 includes situations where the work as actually performed deviated from what
20 was presented to the inspector in order to obtain approval.
21 (3) Concealed Defect Discovered – A defect or code violation is discovered in the
22 approved work that could not reasonably have been observed at the time of
23 the original inspection (for example, a condition that was hidden within a wall,
24 underground, or otherwise concealed), and the defect results in
25 non-compliance with applicable code requirements or presents a safety
26 hazard.
27 (4) Subsequent Damage or Alteration – The approved component or element has
28 been damaged, removed, or altered after the date of the approved inspection
29 in a manner that brings it out of compliance with the Code or the approved
30 plans.
31 If any of the above conditions is met, an inspector may reinspect and require corrective action
32 regarding the previously approved work. In the absence of such conditions, however, the initial
33 approval shall remain valid and the project shall not be deemed in violation of the State Building
34 Code with respect to the aspects of work so approved."
35 SECTION 4.(b) This section becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to
36 building permits applied for on or after that date.
37
38 CREATION OF DISASTER BUILDING INSPECTION RELIEF FUND
39 SECTION 5.(a) Purpose. – The purpose of this section is to create a dedicated fund
40 to support Tier 1 and Tier 2 counties in increasing their building code inspection capacity after a
41 disaster. Such capacity enhancements are critical to ensuring public safety and expediting the
42 recovery of impacted communities.
43 SECTION 5.(b) Definitions. – For purposes of this section, the following definitions
44 apply:
45 (1) County tier system. – The system for designating the economic well-being of
46 counties in the State as established by the North Carolina Department of
47 Commerce pursuant to G.S. 143B-437.08.
48 (2) Disaster. – An event for which the Governor has declared a state of emergency
49 or disaster pursuant to Chapter 166A of the General Statutes.
50 (3) Eligible county. – A county designated as a tier 1 or tier 2 county under the
51 county tier system at the time of the disaster declaration.
Page 8 House Bill 963-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Eligible costs. – Expenditures directly related to the hiring, contracting, or
2 procurement of additional building code inspectors and other personnel
3 necessary to conduct post-disaster inspections, including associated
4 reasonable costs for salaries, contract fees, travel, lodging, overtime, and
5 training expenses incurred after the date of the disaster.
6 (5) OSFM. – The Office of State Fire Marshal.
7 (6) Tier 1 county. – A county designated as tier 1 under the county tier system.
8 (7) Tier 2 county. – A county designated as tier 2 under the county tier system.
9 SECTION 5.(c) Establishment of Fund. – There is established in the Department of
10 Insurance a special fund to be known as the Disaster Building Inspection Relief Fund (Relief
11 Fund). The Relief Fund shall be administered by OSFM. The purpose of the Relief Fund is to
12 provide financial assistance grants to eligible counties for the purpose of hiring additional
13 building code inspectors to support disaster recovery efforts.
14 SECTION 5.(d) Fund Availability and Triggering Event. – Funds within the Relief
15 Fund shall become available for application by eligible counties only upon the Governor's
16 declaration of a state of emergency or disaster pursuant to Chapter 166A of the General Statutes
17 impacting one or more eligible counties.
18 SECTION 5.(e) Eligible Use of Funds. – Funds disbursed from the Relief Fund
19 under this section shall be used by eligible counties solely for eligible costs incurred for the
20 purpose of augmenting building code inspection capacity in response to the declared disaster.
21 Funds may not be used to supplant existing local funding for Code enforcement activities that
22 were budgeted prior to the disaster.
23 SECTION 5.(f) Matching Requirements and Local Contributions. – Funds disbursed
24 from the Relief Fund are subject to the following:
25 (1) Match required. – No eligible county shall receive funds under this section
26 unless, as a condition precedent to the disbursement of funds, the county has
27 documented its commitment to provide a local match from non-State sources.
28 (2) Match percentages. – The required local match shall be calculated as a
29 percentage of the total eligible costs for which the county requests assistance
30 from the Relief Fund, determined as follows:
31 a. Tier 1 counties shall provide a local match equivalent to ten percent
32 (10%) of the requested eligible costs.
33 b. Tier 2 counties shall provide a local match equivalent to twenty-five
34 percent (25%) of the requested eligible costs.
35 SECTION 5.(g) Application and Award Process. – Funds disbursed from the Relief
36 Fund are subject to the following application and award processes:
37 (1) Application. – Following a disaster triggering Relief Fund availability, an
38 eligible county seeking assistance shall submit an application to OSFM.
39 OSFM shall prescribe the application form. The application shall, at a
40 minimum:
41 a. Describe the impact of the disaster on the county's building stock and
42 existing Code-enforcement capacity.
43 b. Provide documentation substantiating the need for additional
44 Code-enforcement personnel resulting from the disaster.
45 c. Outline a plan for utilizing the requested funds, including the number
46 and type of personnel to be hired or contracted and estimated eligible
47 costs.
48 d. Certify the county's commitment to provide the required local match
49 as specified in subsection (f) of this section.
50 (2) Award process. – OSFM shall review applications based on demonstrated
51 need, the severity of the disaster's impact on the county, the feasibility of the
House Bill 963-First Edition Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 county's plan, and compliance with this section. OSFM may award grants to
2 eligible counties on an expedited basis following a disaster declaration to
3 ensure timely inspection services are available to support safe rebuilding
4 efforts. In the event that available funds are insufficient to meet the needs of
5 all qualified applicants, OSFM shall prioritize awards as follows:
6 a. First, to eligible counties designated as a tier 1 county.
7 b. Second, among remaining eligible counties, preference shall be given
8 to those with a total population of less than 200,000 according to the
9 most recent decennial census data.
10 SECTION 5.(h) Reporting. – OSFM shall report on the administration and use of
11 the Relief Fund to the Joint Legislative Commission on Governmental Operations and the Fiscal
12 Research Division. An initial report shall be submitted no later than 90 days after the first grant
13 is awarded from the Relief Fund following a disaster declaration. Subsequent reports shall be
14 submitted annually by November 1. Each report shall include, for the reporting period,
15 information on all grants awarded, the recipient counties, the amount of State funds disbursed
16 and local matching funds provided for each grant, and a summary of the outcomes achieved
17 through the additional inspection support, including any effects on the timeliness of disaster
18 recovery efforts.
19 SECTION 5.(i) Administration. – OSFM is authorized to develop guidelines,
20 procedures, and application forms necessary to implement the provisions of this section.
21
22 PRESERVE LEVEL I CODE-ENFORCEMENT OFFICIALS' AUTHORITY TO
23 INSPECT CERTAIN NONRESIDENTIAL BUILDINGS
24 SECTION 6.(a) Level I Inspections. – Notwithstanding any provision of law to the
25 contrary, an individual who holds a standard certificate as a Code-enforcement official with a
26 level I Building qualification is authorized to conduct inspections on the following types of
27 structures:
28 (1) Small residential buildings. – Residential building up to three stories in height
29 and containing no more than four dwelling units, in accordance with the North
30 Carolina Residential Code.
31 (2) Small nonresidential buildings. – Nonresidential buildings that are no more
32 than one story in height and do not exceed 20,000 square feet in gross floor
33 area, provided such buildings are classified under the North Carolina State
34 Building Code as Business, Mercantile, Factory-Industrial, Storage, or
35 Utility/Miscellaneous occupancies.
36 Level I Code-enforcement officials may perform any inspection within the scope
37 defined in this subsection.
38 SECTION 6.(b) Rulemaking. – The Code Officials Qualification Board shall adopt
39 rules substantively identical to subsection (a) of this section. Rules adopted pursuant to this
40 section are not subject to Part 3 of Article 2A of Chapter 150B of the General Statutes, and such
41 rules shall become effective as provided in G.S. 150B-21.3(b1) as though 10 or more written
42 objections had been received under G.S. 150B-21.3(b2). Until the effective date of the rules the
43 Code Officials Qualification Board is required to adopt pursuant to this section, the Board and
44 local governments shall follow the provisions of subsection (a) of this section as they relate to
45 the buildings level I Code-enforcement officials may inspect.
46 SECTION 6.(c) Sunset. – Subsection (a) of this section expires when the permanent
47 rules adopted as required by subsection (b) of this section become effective.
48
49 EFFECTIVE DATE
50 SECTION 7. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
51 law.
